WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:00.271
it.

00:01.073 --> 00:06.203
Okay, so this paper on a high level deals with model based reinforcement learning.

00:06.965 --> 00:13.638
Model based reinforcement learning means that you are using a model of the world to do reinforcement learning.

00:14.119 --> 00:16.183
So in essence,

00:17.395 --> 00:27.629
If you have your reinforcement learning setup where you are an agent and you have to interact with the world, you have to do so in many steps in like a round trip fashion.

00:27.709 --> 00:41.108
So you put an action, you act and the world gives you back an observation and you have to act in the world over and over and over such that you will be able to maximize your reward.

00:41.088 --> 00:43.778
Now, what is model based reinforcement learning?

00:44.159 --> 00:49.680
Model based reinforcement learning basically means that the agent here has internally

00:51.601 --> 00:52.944
a model of the world.

00:53.445 --> 00:57.092
So it sort of understands how the world works.

00:58.274 --> 01:02.162
Situations where you have a accurate model of the world are things like chess.

01:02.322 --> 01:04.326
So in chess, the rules are very clear.

01:04.386 --> 01:08.534
You know how the world's going to behave if you perform a certain action.

01:08.955 --> 01:14.065
But in real world applications, it's very, very hard to actually make a model.

01:14.045 --> 01:16.769
So people usually rely on learned models.

01:17.230 --> 01:18.071
So what does it mean?

01:18.092 --> 01:23.460
You basically learn a neural network that tries to predict how the world is going to act.

01:24.342 --> 01:30.732
So this here is going to be a deep neural network that you learn from what you see in the world.

01:31.353 --> 01:33.977
Now trajectory optimization

01:33.957 --> 01:50.278
Basically means that you are now you now have this world model and you use it to look ahead as I said so you are in the state like here and you can do let's say three different actions and you use your world model here world.

01:50.258 --> 01:55.126
And you see, you think, how's the world going to react if I do either of those three things?

01:55.366 --> 01:57.169
And then you get into three different states.

01:57.590 --> 02:03.900
And then again, after each one, you consider three actions, three actions here, three actions here, and so on.

02:04.340 --> 02:14.376
So ultimately, you're going to kind of have an overview over a planning horizon, which here we call H. You kind of look ahead a couple of steps.

02:14.356 --> 02:21.928
Or there are various ways of doing this, but ultimately you will basically find that this path here is really good.

02:22.309 --> 02:25.674
So I think I'm going to take this as a first action.

02:28.298 --> 02:37.473
So trajectory optimization considers finding the best green path here in this tree of possibilities that your world model gives you.

02:37.513 --> 02:38.575
Okay.

